Question 2(8.2)

a. correlation matrix p

# convert covariance matrix to correlation matrix
d = sqrt(diag(s))
D <- diag(d)
# find inverse of D
# same as same as matrix(c(d[1], 0, 0, d[2]), nrow = 2, byrow=TRUE)
Dinv <- solve(D)
p <- Dinv %*% s %*% Dinv
round(p, 4)
##        [,1]   [,2]
## [1,] 1.0000 0.6325
## [2,] 0.6325 1.0000
# the whole thing is same as cov2cor(s)

method 1

eigen(p)
## eigen() decomposition
## $values
## [1] 1.6324555 0.3675445
## 
## $vectors
##            [,1]       [,2]
## [1,] -0.7071068  0.7071068
## [2,] -0.7071068 -0.7071068
proportion<- eigen(p)$value[1] / sum(eigen(p)$value)
proportion
## [1] 0.8162278

method 2

pc <- princomp(covmat = p, cor = TRUE)
pc$loading
## 
## Loadings:
##      Comp.1 Comp.2
## [1,]  0.707  0.707
## [2,]  0.707 -0.707
## 
##                Comp.1 Comp.2
## SS loadings       1.0    1.0
## Proportion Var    0.5    0.5
## Cumulative Var    0.5    1.0
summary(pc)
## Importance of components:
##                           Comp.1    Comp.2
## Standard deviation     1.2776758 0.6062545
## Proportion of Variance 0.8162278 0.1837722
## Cumulative Proportion  0.8162278 1.0000000

Two method show the same result. 81.62% of the population variance is explained by the first principal component.
\(Y_1 = 0.707X_1 + 0.707X_2\)
\(Y_2 = 0.707X_1 - 0.707X_2\)

b. compare teh result

The result are different. It is because they are obtain from the different linear transformation matrix (cor and cov). However, they indeed represent the same underlying data set.

c. 90% confidence interval

# using 8-33
# get lambda
eigen(S)$value
## [1] 0.0013676780 0.0007011596 0.0002538024 0.0001426026 0.0001188868
# 90% ci, get alpha
alpha = 0.1
# n = total num of observation
n <- nrow(x)
# p = num of variable
p <- length(x)
ci <- matrix(nrow=2, ncol=p)
for (i in 1:p){
  z <- qnorm(1 - alpha/(2) )
  # calculate ci with 8-33
  upper <- eigen(S)$value[i]/(1-z*sqrt(2/n))
  lower <- eigen(S)$value[i]/(1+z*sqrt(2/n))
  ci[1,i] <- upper
  ci[2,i] <- lower
}
rownames(ci) <- c("Upper Bound", "Lower Bound")
ci
##                    [,1]         [,2]         [,3]         [,4]         [,5]
## Upper Bound 0.001774373 0.0009096574 0.0003292735 0.0001850071 1.542391e-04
## Lower Bound 0.001112653 0.0005704172 0.0002064769 0.0001160121 9.671846e-05
